-- AMSC Shares Decline After Pricing of $155 Million Secondary Offering
-- B y   E h r e n   G o o s s e n s
-- 2010-11-11T18:15:51Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-11/amsc-shares-decline-after-pricing-of-155-million-secondary-offering.html
American Superconductor Corp ., a
maker of wind turbine components and transmission lines, fell
today after the company priced its 4.6 million-share secondary
offering at $35.50 each.  Shares  of the Devens, Massachusetts-based company fell as
much as 5.9 percent in Nasdaq Stock Market trading to $34.74,
their lowest since Nov. 3.  AMSC granted underwriters an over-allotment option to
purchase an additional 690,000 shares. Morgan Stanley & Co.
Inc., Deutsche Bank Securities Inc. and Jefferies & Co. Inc.
were the lead book-running managers and Pacific Crest Securities
LLC was co-manager.  AMSC said Nov. 8 that it intends to use offering proceeds
to expand its superconductor wire production capacity, to pursue
strategic business relationships and for other general purposes. 